here, with this resistor R2,
we could make the transformation

84
00:04:42,891 --> 00:04:45,433
but we would lose the information on the current

85
00:04:45,433 --> 00:04:47,142
that is in the resistor R2.

86
00:04:47,558 --> 00:04:50,808
So, we will apply here the
superposition principle.

87
00:04:50,808 --> 00:04:53,766
To calculate the current i2
passing through the resistor R2,

88
00:04:53,766 --> 00:04:56,681
we see that this current has two components.

89
00:04:56,681 --> 00:05:01,470
A first component that we call i2a,
the subscript a 

90
00:05:01,470 --> 00:05:07,350
corresponding to a response due to the
excitation of the current supply,

91
00:05:08,973 --> 00:05:12,140
plus a component due to

92
00:05:12,855 --> 00:05:16,810
the voltage supply, that we call i2b.

93
00:05:16,810 --> 00:05:24,517
According to the superposition principle,
we can redraw this circuits in two parts

94
00:05:24,517 --> 00:05:27,919
that correspond to the two
components of the supplies.

95
00:05:29,007 --> 00:05:34,065
We have a first component
that only corresponds to

96
00:05:35,802 --> 00:05:37,315
the supply i0.

97
00:05:38,618 --> 00:05:41,282
We represent the resistor R1

98
00:05:42,225 --> 00:05:44,409
with the voltage supply u0
that is cancelled out

99
00:05:46,693 --> 00:05:50,934
and the resistor R2 stays in place.

100
00:05:54,106 --> 00:06:00,107
The current i2a is given here

101
00:06:00,678 --> 00:06:02,315
and we can easily calculate it.

102
00:06:04,905 --> 00:06:10,134
We have that i2 is the sum
of i2a plus i2b

103
00:06:11,410 --> 00:06:15,708
and the current i2a, we recognise
